Dmac_Channel_0_Registers_SAR0 The starting source address is programmed by software before the DMA channel is enabled, or by an LLI update before the start of the DMA transfer. While the DMA transfer is in progress, this register is updated to reflect the source address of the current AHB transfer. Note:You must program the SAR address to be aligned to CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH. The Table "Programming of Transfer Types and Channel Register Update Method" shows how the method of updating the channel registers is a function of LLP.LOC != 0. If LLP.LOC is set to 0x0, then transfers using linked lists are not enabled. This register must be programmed prior to enabling the channel in order to set up the transfer type. - LLP.LOC != 0 contains the pointer to the next LLI for block chaining using linked lists; refer to "Block Chaining Using Linked Lists". The LLPx register can also point to the address where write-back of the control and source/destination status information occur after block completion. Note:You need to program this register to point to the first Linked List Item (LLI) in memory prior to enabling the channel if block chaining is enabled. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". false false false false Rsvd_LMS DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_RSVD_LMS_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 134 Reserved field- read-only 1 0 0x0 R LOC DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_LLP0_LOC_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 147 Starting Address In Memory of next LLI if block chaining is enabled. When the DW_ahb_dmac is the flow controller, the user writes this field before the channel is enabled in order to indicate the block size. The number programmed into BLOCK_TS indicates the total number of single transactions to perform for every block transfer; a single transaction is mapped to a single AMBA beat. Width: The width of single transaction is determined by CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH. For further information on setting this field, refer to "Transfer Operation". Once the transfer starts, the read-back value is the total number of data items already read from the source peripheral, regardless of what is the flow controller. When the source or destination peripheral is assigned as the flow controller, then the maximum block size that can be read back saturates at DMAH_CHx_MAX_BLK_SIZE, but the actual block size can be greater. 39 32 0x02 R/W Rsvd_2_CTL DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_2_CTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 666 Reserved field - read-only 43 40 0x0 R DONE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_DONE_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 697 Done bit. If status write-back is enabled, the upper word of the control register, CTLx[63:32], is written to the control register location of the Linked List Item (LLI) in system memory at the end of the block transfer with the done bit set. Software can poll the LLI CTLx.DONE bit to see when a block transfer is complete. The LLI CTLx.DONE bit should be cleared when the linked lists are set up in memory prior to enabling the channel. LLI accesses are always 32-bit accesses (Hsize=2) aligned to 32-bit boundaries and cannot be changed or programmed to anything other than 32-bit. For more information, refer to "Multi-Block Transfers". 44 44 0x0 R/W true false false DISABLED 0x0 DONE bit is deasserted the enb of block transfer ENABLED 0x1 SET the DONE bit at the end of block transfer Rsvd_3_CTL DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CTL0_RSVD_3_CTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 705 Reserved field - read-only 63 45 0x00000 R register dmac.Channel_0_Registers.SSTAT0 SSTAT0 DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_SSTAT0_ADDRESS DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_SSTAT0_BYTE_ADDRESS DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_SSTAT0_OFFSET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_SSTAT0_BYTE_OFFSET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 749 Source Status Register for Channel x 0x20 R/W 0x0000000000000000 Dmac_Channel_0_Registers_SSTAT0 After each block transfer completes, hardware can retrieve the source status information from the address pointed to by the contents of the SSTATARx register. This status information is then stored in the SSTATx register and written out to the SSTATx register location of the LLI before the start of the next block. For conditions under which the source status information is fetched, refer to "Multi-Block Transfers". This register does not exist if DMAH_CHx_STAT_SRC is set to False; in this case, the read-back value is always 0. Note: This register is a temporary placeholder for the source status information on its way to the SSTATx register location of the LLI. The source status information should be retrieved by software from the SSTATx register location of the LLI, and not by a read of this register over the DW_ahb_dmac slave interface. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. The user can select any location in system memory that would provide a 32-bit value to indicate the status of the source transfer. For example, if the DW_apb_ssi is the source peripheral for the DMA transfer, the user can use one of the SSI registers to indicate the status of the transfer. Thus the address programmed in SSTATARx could be the address of the SSI.CTRL register or the SSI.ISR register, or it could be the address of the SSI.RXFLR register. Note: If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". PROTCTL DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_PROTCTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 1244 Protection Control bits used to drive the AHB HPROT[3:1] bus. The AMBA Specification recommends that the default of HPROT indicates a non-cached, non-buffered, privileged data access. The reset value is used to indicate such an access. HPROT[0] is tied high because all transfers are data accesses, as there are no opcode fetches. There is a one-to-one mapping of these register bits to the HPROT[3:1] master interface signals. Mapping of HPROT bus is as follows: - 1'b1 to HPROT[0] - CFGx.PROTCTL[1] to HPROT[1] - CFGx.PROTCTL[2] to HPROT[2] - CFGx.PROTCTL[3] to HPROT[3] 36 34 0x1 R/W DS_UPD_EN DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_0_REGISTERS_CFG0_DS_UPD_EN_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 1268 Destination Status Update Enable. This is defined as a gather boundary. - Source gather interval field (SGRx.SGI) Specifies the source address increment/decrement in multiples of CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH on a gather boundary when gather mode is enabled for the source transfer. Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". The CTLx.SINC field controls whether the address increments or decrements. When the CTLx.SINC field indicates a fixed-address control, then the address remains constant throughout the transfer and the SGRx register is ignored. This register does not exist if the configuration parameter DMAH_CHx_SRC_GAT_EN is set to False. Note: If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". The CTLx.DINC field controls whether the address increments or decrements. When the CTLx.DINC field indicates a fixed address control, then the address remains constant throughout the transfer and the DSRx register is ignored. This register does not exist if the configuration parameter DMAH_CHx_DST_SCA_EN is set to False. The Table "Programming of Transfer Types and Channel Register Update Method" shows how the method of updating the channel registers is a function of LLP.LOC != 0. If LLP.LOC is set to 0x0, then transfers using linked lists are not enabled. This register must be programmed prior to enabling the channel in order to set up the transfer type. - LLP.LOC != 0 contains the pointer to the next LLI for block chaining using linked lists; refer to "Block Chaining Using Linked Lists". The LLPx register can also point to the address where write-back of the control and source/destination status information occur after block completion. Note:You need to program this register to point to the first Linked List Item (LLI) in memory prior to enabling the channel if block chaining is enabled. When the DW_ahb_dmac is the flow controller, the user writes this field before the channel is enabled in order to indicate the block size. The number programmed into BLOCK_TS indicates the total number of single transactions to perform for every block transfer; a single transaction is mapped to a single AMBA beat. Width: The width of single transaction is determined by CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH. For further information on setting this field, refer to "Transfer Operation". Once the transfer starts, the read-back value is the total number of data items already read from the source peripheral, regardless of what is the flow controller. When the source or destination peripheral is assigned as the flow controller, then the maximum block size that can be read back saturates at DMAH_CHx_MAX_BLK_SIZE, but the actual block size can be greater. 39 32 0x02 R/W Rsvd_2_CTL DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_RSVD_2_CTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2078 Reserved field - read-only 43 40 0x0 R DONE DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CTL1_DONE_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2109 Done bit. If status write-back is enabled, the upper word of the control register, CTLx[63:32], is written to the control register location of the Linked List Item (LLI) in system memory at the end of the block transfer with the done bit set. Software can poll the LLI CTLx.DONE bit to see when a block transfer is complete. The LLI CTLx.DONE bit should be cleared when the linked lists are set up in memory prior to enabling the channel. LLI accesses are always 32-bit accesses (Hsize=2) aligned to 32-bit boundaries and cannot be changed or programmed to anything other than 32-bit. The source status information should be retrieved by software from the SSTATx register location of the LLI, and not by a read of this register over the DW_ahb_dmac slave interface. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. PROTCTL DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_PROTCTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2656 Protection Control bits used to drive the AHB HPROT[3:1] bus. The AMBA Specification recommends that the default of HPROT indicates a non-cached, non-buffered, privileged data access. The reset value is used to indicate such an access. HPROT[0] is tied high because all transfers are data accesses, as there are no opcode fetches. There is a one-to-one mapping of these register bits to the HPROT[3:1] master interface signals. Mapping of HPROT bus is as follows: - 1'b1 to HPROT[0] - CFGx.PROTCTL[1] to HPROT[1] - CFGx.PROTCTL[2] to HPROT[2] - CFGx.PROTCTL[3] to HPROT[3] 36 34 0x1 R/W DS_UPD_EN DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_CFG1_DS_UPD_EN_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2680 Destination Status Update Enable. This is defined as a gather boundary. - Source gather interval field (SGRx.SGI) Specifies the source address increment/decrement in multiples of CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH on a gather boundary when gather mode is enabled for the source transfer. Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". The CTLx.SINC field controls whether the address increments or decrements. When the CTLx.SINC field indicates a fixed-address control, then the address remains constant throughout the transfer and the SGRx register is ignored. This register does not exist if the configuration parameter DMAH_CHx_SRC_GAT_EN is set to False. For more information, see "Scatter/Gather". false false false false SGI DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGI_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2763 Source Gather Interval. 19 0 0x00000 R/W SGC DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_1_REGISTERS_SGR1_SGC_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2771 Source Gather Count. The Table "Programming of Transfer Types and Channel Register Update Method" shows how the method of updating the channel registers is a function of LLP.LOC != 0. If LLP.LOC is set to 0x0, then transfers using linked lists are not enabled. This register must be programmed prior to enabling the channel in order to set up the transfer type. - LLP.LOC != 0 contains the pointer to the next LLI for block chaining using linked lists; refer to "Block Chaining Using Linked Lists". The LLPx register can also point to the address where write-back of the control and source/destination status information occur after block completion. Note:You need to program this register to point to the first Linked List Item (LLI) in memory prior to enabling the channel if block chaining is enabled. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". false false false false Rsvd_LMS DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_RSVD_LMS_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2958 Reserved field- read-only 1 0 0x0 R LOC DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_LLP2_LOC_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 2971 Starting Address In Memory of next LLI if block chaining is enabled. When the DW_ahb_dmac is the flow controller, the user writes this field before the channel is enabled in order to indicate the block size. The number programmed into BLOCK_TS indicates the total number of single transactions to perform for every block transfer; a single transaction is mapped to a single AMBA beat. Width: The width of single transaction is determined by CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH. For further information on setting this field, refer to "Transfer Operation". Once the transfer starts, the read-back value is the total number of data items already read from the source peripheral, regardless of what is the flow controller. When the source or destination peripheral is assigned as the flow controller, then the maximum block size that can be read back saturates at DMAH_CHx_MAX_BLK_SIZE, but the actual block size can be greater. 39 32 0x02 R/W Rsvd_2_CTL DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_RSVD_2_CTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 3490 Reserved field - read-only 43 40 0x0 R DONE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CTL2_DONE_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 3521 Done bit. If status write-back is enabled, the upper word of the control register, CTLx[63:32], is written to the control register location of the Linked List Item (LLI) in system memory at the end of the block transfer with the done bit set. Software can poll the LLI CTLx.DONE bit to see when a block transfer is complete. The LLI CTLx.DONE bit should be cleared when the linked lists are set up in memory prior to enabling the channel. LLI accesses are always 32-bit accesses (Hsize=2) aligned to 32-bit boundaries and cannot be changed or programmed to anything other than 32-bit. The source status information should be retrieved by software from the SSTATx register location of the LLI, and not by a read of this register over the DW_ahb_dmac slave interface. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. The user can select any location in system memory that would provide a 32-bit value to indicate the status of the source transfer. For example, if the DW_apb_ssi is the source peripheral for the DMA transfer, the user can use one of the SSI registers to indicate the status of the transfer. Thus the address programmed in SSTATARx could be the address of the SSI.CTRL register or the SSI.ISR register, or it could be the address of the SSI.RXFLR register. Note: If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". Data pre-fetching is enabled FCMODE_1 0x1 Source transaction requests are not serviced until a destination transaction request occurs. In this mode, the amount of data transferred from the source is limited so that it is guaranteed to be transferred to the destination prior to block termination by the destination. Data pre-fetching is disabled. The exceptions are at the end of a burst transaction request or at the end of a block transfer. PROTCTL DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_PROTCTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 4068 Protection Control bits used to drive the AHB HPROT[3:1] bus. The AMBA Specification recommends that the default of HPROT indicates a non-cached, non-buffered, privileged data access. The reset value is used to indicate such an access. HPROT[0] is tied high because all transfers are data accesses, as there are no opcode fetches. There is a one-to-one mapping of these register bits to the HPROT[3:1] master interface signals. Mapping of HPROT bus is as follows: - 1'b1 to HPROT[0] - CFGx.PROTCTL[1] to HPROT[1] - CFGx.PROTCTL[2] to HPROT[2] - CFGx.PROTCTL[3] to HPROT[3] 36 34 0x1 R/W DS_UPD_EN DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_CFG2_DS_UPD_EN_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 4092 Destination Status Update Enable. This is defined as a gather boundary. - Source gather interval field (SGRx.SGI) Specifies the source address increment/decrement in multiples of CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH on a gather boundary when gather mode is enabled for the source transfer. Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". The CTLx.SINC field controls whether the address increments or decrements. When the CTLx.SINC field indicates a fixed-address control, then the address remains constant throughout the transfer and the SGRx register is ignored. This register does not exist if the configuration parameter DMAH_CHx_SRC_GAT_EN is set to False. For more information, see "Scatter/Gather". false false false false SGI DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGI_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 4175 Source Gather Interval. 19 0 0x00000 R/W SGC DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_2_REGISTERS_SGR2_SGC_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 4183 Source Gather Count. The Table "Programming of Transfer Types and Channel Register Update Method" shows how the method of updating the channel registers is a function of LLP.LOC != 0. If LLP.LOC is set to 0x0, then transfers using linked lists are not enabled. This register must be programmed prior to enabling the channel in order to set up the transfer type. - LLP.LOC != 0 contains the pointer to the next LLI for block chaining using linked lists; refer to "Block Chaining Using Linked Lists". The LLPx register can also point to the address where write-back of the control and source/destination status information occur after block completion. Note:You need to program this register to point to the first Linked List Item (LLI) in memory prior to enabling the channel if block chaining is enabled. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. When the DW_ahb_dmac is the flow controller, the user writes this field before the channel is enabled in order to indicate the block size. The number programmed into BLOCK_TS indicates the total number of single transactions to perform for every block transfer; a single transaction is mapped to a single AMBA beat. Width: The width of single transaction is determined by CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH. For further information on setting this field, refer to "Transfer Operation". Once the transfer starts, the read-back value is the total number of data items already read from the source peripheral, regardless of what is the flow controller. When the source or destination peripheral is assigned as the flow controller, then the maximum block size that can be read back saturates at DMAH_CHx_MAX_BLK_SIZE, but the actual block size can be greater. 39 32 0x02 R/W Rsvd_2_CTL DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_RSVD_2_CTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 4905 Reserved field - read-only 43 40 0x0 R DONE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CTL3_DONE_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 4936 Done bit. If status write-back is enabled, the upper word of the control register, CTLx[63:32], is written to the control register location of the Linked List Item (LLI) in system memory at the end of the block transfer with the done bit set. Software can poll the LLI CTLx.DONE bit to see when a block transfer is complete. The LLI CTLx.DONE bit should be cleared when the linked lists are set up in memory prior to enabling the channel. LLI accesses are always 32-bit accesses (Hsize=2) aligned to 32-bit boundaries and cannot be changed or programmed to anything other than 32-bit. Note: This register is a temporary placeholder for the source status information on its way to the SSTATx register location of the LLI. The source status information should be retrieved by software from the SSTATx register location of the LLI, and not by a read of this register over the DW_ahb_dmac slave interface. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. The user can select any location in system memory that would provide a 32-bit value to indicate the status of the source transfer. For example, if the DW_apb_ssi is the source peripheral for the DMA transfer, the user can use one of the SSI registers to indicate the status of the transfer. Thus the address programmed in SSTATARx could be the address of the SSI.CTRL register or the SSI.ISR register, or it could be the address of the SSI.RXFLR register. Note: If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". Determines when source transaction requests are serviced when the Destination Peripheral is the flow controller. 32 32 0x0 R/W true false false FCMODE_0 0x0 Source transaction requests are serviced when they occur. Data pre-fetching is enabled FCMODE_1 0x1 Source transaction requests are not serviced until a destination transaction request occurs. In this mode, the amount of data transferred from the source is limited so that it is guaranteed to be transferred to the destination prior to block termination by the destination. Data pre-fetching is disabled. FIFO_MODE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_FIFO_MODE_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 5463 FIFO Mode Select. Determines how much space or data needs to be available in the FIFO before a burst transaction request is serviced. 33 33 0x0 R/W true false false FIFO_MODE_0 0x0 Space/data available for single AHB transfer of the specified transfer width FIFO_MODE_1 0x1 Data available is greater than or equal to half the FIFO depth for destination transfers and space available is greater than half the fifo depth for source transfers. The exceptions are at the end of a burst transaction request or at the end of a block transfer. PROTCTL DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_PROTCTL_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 5483 Protection Control bits used to drive the AHB HPROT[3:1] bus. The AMBA Specification recommends that the default of HPROT indicates a non-cached, non-buffered, privileged data access. The reset value is used to indicate such an access. HPROT[0] is tied high because all transfers are data accesses, as there are no opcode fetches. There is a one-to-one mapping of these register bits to the HPROT[3:1] master interface signals. Mapping of HPROT bus is as follows: - 1'b1 to HPROT[0] - CFGx.PROTCTL[1] to HPROT[1] - CFGx.PROTCTL[2] to HPROT[2] - CFGx.PROTCTL[3] to HPROT[3] 36 34 0x1 R/W DS_UPD_EN DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_CFG3_DS_UPD_EN_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 5507 Destination Status Update Enable. This is defined as a gather boundary. - Source gather interval field (SGRx.SGI) Specifies the source address increment/decrement in multiples of CTLx.SRC_TR_WIDTH on a gather boundary when gather mode is enabled for the source transfer. Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. For more information, refer to "Illegal Register Access". The CTLx.SINC field controls whether the address increments or decrements. When the CTLx.SINC field indicates a fixed-address control, then the address remains constant throughout the transfer and the SGRx register is ignored. This register does not exist if the configuration parameter DMAH_CHx_SRC_GAT_EN is set to False. For more information, see "Scatter/Gather". false false false false SGI DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGI_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 5590 Source Gather Interval. 19 0 0x00000 R/W SGC DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_WIDTH DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_MSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_LSB DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_RANGE DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_RESET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_FIELD_MASK DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_GET DMAC_CHANNEL_3_REGISTERS_SGR3_SGC_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 5598 Source Gather Count. A channel INT_MASK bit will be written only if the corresponding mask write enable bit in the INT_MASK_WE field is asserted on the same AHB write transfer. This allows software to set a mask bit without performing a read-modified write operation. For example, writing hex 01x1 to the MaskTfr register writes a 1 into MaskTfr[0], while MaskTfr[7:1] remains unchanged. Writing hex 00xx leaves MaskTfr[7:0] unchanged. R/W 0x0000000000000000 Dmac_Interrupt_Registers_MaskSrcTran The contents of the Raw Status register RawSrcTran is masked with the contents of the Mask register MaskSrcTran. Each bit of register is allocated per channel; for example, MaskSrcTran[2] is the mask bit for the Channel 2 source transaction complete interrupt. When the source peripheral of DMA channel i is memory, then the source transaction complete interrupt, MaskSrcTran[i], must be masked to prevent an erroneous triggering of an interrupt on the int_combined signal. A channel INT_MASK bit will be written only if the corresponding mask write enable bit in the INT_MASK_WE field is asserted on the same AHB write transfer. This allows software to set a mask bit without performing a read-modified write operation. For example, writing hex 01x1 to the MaskSrcTran register writes a 1 into MaskSrcTran[0], while MaskSrcTran[7:1] remains unchanged. Writing hex 00xx leaves MaskSrcTran[7:0] unchanged. Writing a 1 to any bit in this register unmasks the corresponding interrupt, thus allowing the DW_ahb_dmac to set the appropriate bit in the Status registers and int_* port signals. false false false dmac.Interrupt_Registers.MaskDstTran MaskDstTran DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_ADDRESS DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_BYTE_ADDRESS DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_OFFSET DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_BYTE_OFFSET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 6374 Mask for IntDstTran Interrupt 0x68 R/W 0x0000000000000000 Dmac_Interrupt_Registers_MaskDstTran The contents of the Raw Status register RawDstTran is masked with the contents of the Mask register MaskDstTran. Each bit of register is allocated per channel; for example, MaskDstTran[2] is the mask bit for the Channel 2 destination transaction complete interrupt. When the destination peripheral of DMA channel i is memory, then the destination transaction complete interrupt, MaskDstTran[i], must be masked to prevent an erroneous triggering of an interrupt on the int_combined(_n) signal. A channel INT_MASK bit will be written only if the corresponding mask write enable bit in the INT_MASK_WE field is asserted on the same AHB write transfer. This allows software to set a mask bit without performing a read-modified write operation. For example, writing hex 01x1 to the MaskDstTran register writes a 1 into MaskDstTran[0], while MaskDstTran[7:1] remains unchanged. Writing hex 00xx leaves MaskDstTran[7:0] unchanged. Writing a 1 to any bit in this register unmasks the corresponding interrupt, thus allowing the DW_ahb_dmac to set the appropriate bit in the Status registers and int_* port signals. false false false false INT_MASK DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_WIDTH DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_MSB DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_LSB DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_RANGE DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_RESET DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_FIELD_MASK DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_GET DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_INT_MASK_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 6338 Mask for IntDstTran Interrupt 3 0 0x0 R/W true false false MASK 0x0 Mask the interrupts UNMASK 0x1 Unmask the interrupts Rsvd_MaskDstTran DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_WIDTH DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_MSB DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_LSB DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_RANGE DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_RESET DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_FIELD_MASK DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_GET DMAC_INTERRUPT_REGISTERS_MASKDSTTRAN_RSVD_MASKDSTTRAN_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 6346 Reserved field - dmac.Software_Handshake_Registers.ReqSrcReg ReqSrcReg DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_ADDRESS DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_BYTE_ADDRESS DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_OFFSET DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_BYTE_OFFSET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 6811 Source Software Transaction Request register 0x0 R/W 0x0000000000000000 Dmac_Software_Handshake_Registers_ReqSrcReg A bit is assigned for each channel in this register. ReqSrcReg[n] is ignored when software handshaking is not enabled for the source of channel n. A channel SRC_REQ bit is written only if the corresponding channel write enable bit in the SRC_REQ_WE field is asserted on the same AHB write transfer, and if the channel is enabled in the ChEnReg register. For example, writing hex 0101 writes a 1 into ReqSrcReg[0], while ReqSrcReg[7:1] remains unchanged. Writing hex 00xx leaves ReqSrcReg[7:0] unchanged. This allows software to set a bit in the ReqSrcReg register without performing a read-modified write operation. The functionality of this register depends on whether the source is a flow control peripheral or not. For a description of when the source is not a flow controller, refer to "Software Handshaking Peripheral Is Not Flow Controller". For a description of when the source is a flow controller, refer to "Software Handshaking Peripheral Is Flow Controller" false false false false SRC_REQ DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_WIDTH DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_MSB DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_LSB DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_RANGE DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_RESET DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_FIELD_MASK DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_GET DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_SRC_REQ_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 6775 Source Software Transaction Request 3 0 0x0 R/W true false false ACTIVE 0x1 Source request is active INACTIVE 0x0 Source request is not active Rsvd_ReqSrcReg DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_WIDTH DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_MSB DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_LSB DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_RANGE DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_RESET DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_FIELD_MASK DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_GET DMAC_SOFTWARE_HANDSHAKE_REGISTERS_REQSRCREG_RSVD_REQSRCREG_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 6783 Reserved field - If software needs to set up a new channel, then it can read this register in order to find out which channels are currently inactive; it can then enable an inactive channel with the required priority. All bits of this register are cleared to 0 when the global DW_ahb_dmac channel enable bit, DmaCfgReg[0], is 0. When the global channel enable bit is 0, then a write to the ChEnReg register is ignored and a read will always read back 0. The channel enable bit, ChEnReg.CH_EN, is written only if the corresponding channel write enable bit, ChEnReg.CH_EN_WE, is asserted on the same AHB write transfer. For example, writing hex 01x1 writes a 1 into ChEnReg[0], while ChEnReg[7:1] remains unchanged. Writing hex 00xx leaves ChEnReg[7:0] unchanged. Note that a read-modified write is not required. For information on software disabling a channel by writing 0 to ChEnReg.CH_EN, refer to "Disabling a Channel Prior to Transfer Completion". false false false false CH_EN DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_WIDTH DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_MSB DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_LSB DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_RANGE DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_RESET DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_FIELD_MASK DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_GET DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_CHENREG_CH_EN_SET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 7252 Channel Enable. Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_DMA_COMP_PARAMS_3_OFFSET DMAC_MISCELLANEOUS_REGISTERS_DMA_COMP_PARAMS_3_BYTE_OFFSET DW_ahb_dmac.csr 10874 DW_ahb_dmac Component Parameters Register 3 0x48 R 0x1002dbc01002dbc0 Dmac_Miscellaneous_Registers_DMA_COMP_PARAMS_3 DMA_COMP_PARAMS_3 is a constant read-only register that contains encoded information about the component parameter settings for Channel 1 and Channel 2. The reset value depends on coreConsultant parameter(s). Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response. The reset value depends on coreConsultant parameter(s). Note:If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to True, the DW_ahb_dmac returns an ERROR response to an illegal register access, which includes accessing registers that have been removed during DW_ahb_dmac configuration. If DMAH_RETURN_ERR_RESP is set to False, DW_ahb_dmac always returns an OK response.
